[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Since its inception, HTML and its associated protocols gained acceptance relatively quickly. However, no clear standards existed in the early years of the language. Though its creators originally conceived of HTML as a semantic language devoid of presentation details,
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-69
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML?oldformat=true#cite_note-69
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 69
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] practical uses pushed many presentational elements and attributes into the language, driven largely by the various browser vendors. The latest standards surrounding HTML reflect efforts to overcome the sometimes chaotic development of the language
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-70
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML?oldformat=true#cite_note-70
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 70
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and to create a rational foundation for building both meaningful and well-presented documents. To return HTML to its role as a semantic language, the
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Wide_Web_Consortium
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] World Wide Web Consortium
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] W3C
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] has developed style languages such as
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cascading_Style_Sheets
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Cascading Style Sheets
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] CSS
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extensible_Stylesheet_Language
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Extensible Stylesheet Language
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-redirect
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] XSL
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] to shoulder the burden of presentation. In conjunction, the HTML specification has slowly reined in the presentational elements.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] There are two axes differentiating various variations of HTML as currently specified: SGML-based HTML versus XML-based HTML (referred to as XHTML) on one axis, and strict versus transitional (loose) versus frameset on the other axis.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <h3
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-headline
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] SGML-based_versus_XML-based_HTML
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] SGML-based versus XML-based HTML
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-editsection
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-editsection-bracket
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=HTML&action=edit&section=20
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Edit section: SGML-based versus XML-based HTML
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] edit
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-editsection-bracket
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </h3
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] One difference in the latest HTML specifications lies in the distinction between the SGML-based specification and the XML-based specification. The XML-based specification is usually called
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XHTML
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] XHTML
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] XHTML
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] to distinguish it clearly from the more traditional definition. However, the root element name continues to be "html" even in the XHTML-specified HTML. The W3C intended XHTML 1.0 to be identical to HTML 4.01 except where limitations of XML over the more complex SGML require workarounds. Because XHTML and HTML are closely related, they are sometimes documented in parallel. In such circumstances, some authors
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/(X)HTML
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] (X)HTML
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-redirect
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] conflate the two names
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] as (X)HTML or X(HTML).
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Like HTML 4.01, XHTML 1.0 has three sub-specifications: strict, transitional and frameset.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Aside from the different opening declarations for a document, the differences between an HTML 4.01 and XHTML 1.0 document—in each of the corresponding DTDs—are largely syntactic. The underlying syntax of HTML allows many shortcuts that XHTML does not, such as elements with optional opening or closing tags, and even empty elements which must not have an end tag. By contrast, XHTML requires all elements to have an opening tag and a closing tag. XHTML, however, also introduces a new shortcut: an XHTML tag may be opened and closed within the same tag, by including a slash before the end of the tag like this:
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;br/&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] . The introduction of this shorthand, which is not used in the SGML declaration for HTML 4.01, may confuse earlier software unfamiliar with this new convention. A fix for this is to include a space before closing the tag, as such:
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;br /&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] .
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-71
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML?oldformat=true#cite_note-71
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 71
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] To understand the subtle differences between HTML and XHTML, consider the transformation of a valid and well-formed XHTML 1.0 document that adheres to Appendix C (see below) into a valid HTML 4.01 document. To make this translation requires the following steps:
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <ol
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The language for an element should be specified with a
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] lang
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] attribute rather than the XHTML
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] xml:lang
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] attribute.
[End Tag        ] </b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] XHTML uses XML's built in language-defining functionality attribute.
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Remove the XML namespace (
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] xmlns=URI
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ).
[End Tag        ] </b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] HTML has no facilities for namespaces.
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Change the document type declaration
[End Tag        ] </b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] from XHTML 1.0 to HTML 4.01. (see
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML?oldformat=true#Document_type_declaration
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] DTD section
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] for further explanation).
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] If present,
[Start Tag      ] <b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] remove the XML declaration.
[End Tag        ] </b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (Typically this is:
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ).
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Ensure that the document's MIME type is set to
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] text/html
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] .
[End Tag        ] </b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] For both HTML and XHTML, this comes from the HTTP
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Content-Type
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] header sent by the server.
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Change the XML empty-element syntax to an HTML style empty element
[End Tag        ] </b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;br/&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] to
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;br&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ).
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </ol
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Those are the main changes necessary to translate a document from XHTML 1.0 to HTML 4.01. To translate from HTML to XHTML would also require the addition of any omitted opening or closing tags. Whether coding in HTML or XHTML it may just be best to always include the optional tags within an HTML document rather than remembering which tags can be omitted.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] A well-formed XHTML document adheres to all the syntax requirements of XML. A valid document adheres to the content specification for XHTML, which describes the document structure.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The W3C recommends several conventions to ensure an easy migration between HTML and XHTML (see
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] rel
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] nofollow
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] external text
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/#guidelines
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] HTML Compatibility Guidelines
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ). The following steps can be applied to XHTML 1.0 documents only:
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <ul
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Include both
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] xml:lang
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] lang
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] attributes on any elements assigning language.
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Use the empty-element syntax only for elements specified as empty in HTML.
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Include an extra space in empty-element tags: for example
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;br /&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] instead of
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;br/&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] .
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Include explicit close tags for elements that permit content but are left empty (for example,
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;div&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;/div&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] , not
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;div /&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ).
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Omit the XML declaration.
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </ul
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] By carefully following the W3C's compatibility guidelines, a user agent should be able to interpret the document equally as HTML or XHTML. For documents that are XHTML 1.0 and have been made compatible in this way, the W3C permits them to be served either as HTML (with a
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] text/html
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MIME_type
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] MIME type
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-redirect
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] MIME type
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ), or as XHTML (with an
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] application/xhtml+xml
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] or
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] application/xml
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] MIME type). When delivered as XHTML, browsers should use an XML parser, which adheres strictly to the XML specifications for parsing the document's contents.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <h3
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-headline
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Transitional_versus_strict
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Transitional versus strict
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-editsection
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-editsection-bracket
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=HTML&action=edit&section=21
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Edit section: Transitional versus strict
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] edit
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-editsection-bracket
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </h3
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] HTML 4 defined three different versions of the language: Strict, Transitional (once called Loose) and Frameset. The Strict version is intended for new documents and is considered best practice, while the Transitional and Frameset versions were developed to make it easier to transition documents that conformed to older HTML specification or didn't conform to any specification to a version of HTML 4. The Transitional and Frameset versions allow for
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Presentational_markup&action=edit&redlink=1
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] new
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Presentational markup (page does not exist)
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] presentational markup
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] , which is omitted in the Strict version. Instead,
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cascading_style_sheets
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Cascading style sheets
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-redirect
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] cascading style sheets
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] are encouraged to improve the presentation of HTML documents. Because XHTML 1 only defines an XML syntax for the language defined by HTML 4, the same differences apply to XHTML 1 as well.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The Transitional version allows the following parts of the vocabulary, which are not included in the Strict version:
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <ul
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] A looser content model
[End Tag        ] </b
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <ul
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Inline elements and plain text are allowed directly in:
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] body
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ,
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] blockquote
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ,
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] form
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ,
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] noscript
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] noframes
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </ul
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Presentation related elements
[End Tag        ] </b
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <ul
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] underline (
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] u
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] )(Deprecated. can confuse a visitor with a hyperlink.)
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] strike-through (
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] s
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] )
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] center
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (Deprecated. use CSS instead.)
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] font
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (Deprecated. use CSS instead.)
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] basefont
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (Deprecated. use CSS instead.)
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </ul
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <b
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Presentation related attributes
[End Tag        ] </b
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <ul
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] background
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (Deprecated. use CSS instead.) and
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] bgcolor
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (Deprecated. use CSS instead.) attributes for
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] body
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (required element according to the W3C.) element.
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] align
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (Deprecated. use CSS instead.) attribute on
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] div
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ,
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] form
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] , paragraph (
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] p
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ) and heading (
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] h1
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ...
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] h6
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ) elements
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] align
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (Deprecated. use CSS instead.),
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] noshade
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (Deprecated. use CSS instead.),
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] size
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (Deprecated. use CSS instead.) and
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] width
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (Deprecated. use CSS instead.) attributes on
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] hr

[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The Frameset version includes everything in the Transitional version, as well as the
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] frameset
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] element (used instead of
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] body
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ) and the
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] frame
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] element.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <h3
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-headline
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Frameset_versus_transitional
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Frameset versus transitional
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-editsection
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-editsection-bracket
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=HTML&action=edit&section=22
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Edit section: Frameset versus transitional
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] edit
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-editsection-bracket
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </h3
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] In addition to the above transitional differences, the frameset specifications (whether XHTML 1.0 or HTML 4.01) specify a different content model, with
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] frameset
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] replacing
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] body
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] , that contains either
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] frame
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] elements, or optionally
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] noframes
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] with a
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] body
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] .
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <h3
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-headline
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Summary_of_specification_versions
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Summary of specification versions
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-editsection
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-editsection-bracket
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=HTML&action=edit&section=23
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Edit section: Summary of specification versions
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] edit
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-editsection-bracket
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </h3
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] As this list demonstrates, the loose versions of the specification are maintained for legacy support. However, contrary to popular misconceptions, the move to XHTML does not imply a removal of this legacy support. Rather the X in XML stands for extensible and the W3C is modularizing the entire specification and opening it up to independent extensions. The primary achievement in the move from XHTML 1.0 to XHTML 1.1 is the modularization of the entire specification. The strict version of HTML is deployed in XHTML 1.1 through a set of modular extensions to the base XHTML 1.1 specification. Likewise, someone looking for the loose (transitional) or frameset specifications will find similar extended XHTML 1.1 support (much of it is contained in the legacy or frame modules). The modularization also allows for separate features to develop on their own timetable. So for example, XHTML 1.1 will allow quicker migration to emerging XML standards such as
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MathML
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] MathML
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] MathML
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (a presentational and semantic math language based on XML) and
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XForms
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] XForms
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] XForms
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] —a new highly advanced web-form technology to replace the existing HTML forms.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] In summary, the HTML 4 specification primarily reined in all the various HTML implementations into a single clearly written specification based on SGML. XHTML 1.0, ported this specification, as is, to the new XML defined specification. Next, XHTML 1.1 takes advantage of the extensible nature of XML and modularizes the whole specification. XHTML 2.0 was intended to be the first step in adding new features to the specification in a standards-body-based approach.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >

[Text           ] following the W3C process. As of 2013

[Text           ] both specifications are similar and mostly derived from each other, i.e., the work on HTML5 started with an older WhatWG draft, and later the WhatWG

[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =

[Text           ] Hypertext features not in HTML
[End Tag        ] </span

[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] HTML lacks some of the features found in earlier hypertext systems, such as
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Source_tracking
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Source tracking
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] source tracking
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ,
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fat_link
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Fat link
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] fat links
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and others.
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-74
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML?oldformat=true#cite_note-74
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 74
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Even some hypertext features that were in early versions of HTML have been ignored by most popular web browsers until recently, such as the link element and in-browser Web page editing.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Sometimes Web services or browser manufacturers remedy these shortcomings. For instance,
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wiki
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Wiki
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] wikis
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] and
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Content_management_system
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Content management system
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] content management systems
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] allow surfers to edit the Web pages they visit.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <h2
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-headline
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] WYSIWYG_editors
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] WYSIWYG editors
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-editsection
[Tag End        ] >

[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-editsection-bracket
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=HTML&action=edit&section=27
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Edit section: WYSIWYG editors
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] edit
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-editsection-bracket
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </h2
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] There are some
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WYSIWYG
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] WYSIWYG
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] WYSIWYG
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] editors (What You See Is What You Get), in which the user lays out everything as it is to appear in the HTML document using a
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graphical_user_interface
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Graphical user interface
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] graphical user interface
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] (GUI), often similar to
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Word_processor
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Word processor
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] word processors
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] . The editor renders the document rather than show the code, so authors do not require extensive knowledge of HTML.
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The WYSIWYG editing model has been criticized,
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-75
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML?oldformat=true#cite_note-75
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 75
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-76
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML?oldformat=true#cite_note-76
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 76
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] primarily because of the low quality of the generated code; there are voices advocating a change to the
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WYSIWYM
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] WYSIWYM
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] WYSIWYM
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] model (What You See Is What You Mean).
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <p
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] WYSIWYG editors remain a controversial topic because of their perceived flaws such as:
[End Tag        ] </p
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <ul
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Relying mainly on layout as opposed to meaning, often using markup that does not convey the intended meaning but simply copies the layout.
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-77
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTML?oldformat=true#cite_note-77
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 77
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Often producing extremely verbose and redundant code that fails to make use of the cascading nature of HTML and
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CSS
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] CSS
[Attribute Name ] class
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] mw-redirect
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] CSS
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] .
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Often producing ungrammatical markup often called
[Start Tag      ] <a
[Attribute Name ] href
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tag_soup
[Attribute Name ] title
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] Tag soup
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] tag soup
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] or semantically incorrect markup (such as
[Start Tag      ] <code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] &lt;em&gt;
[End Tag        ] </code
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] for italics).
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <li
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] As a great deal of the information in HTML documents is not in the layout, the model has been criticized for its "what you see is all you get"-nature.
[Start Tag      ] <sup
[Attribute Name ] id
[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] cite_ref-78

[Equal Sign     ] =
[Attribute Value] reference
[Tag End        ] >

[Equal Sign     ] =

[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] [
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] 78
[Start Tag      ] <span
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] ]
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </sup
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </li
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </ul
[Tag End        ] >

[Tag End        ] >
[Start Tag      ] <i
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] The Art of Unix Programming
[End Tag        ] </i
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] .
[Start Tag      ] <q
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] In IETF tradition, standards have to arise from experience with a working prototype implementation&nbsp;— but once they become standards, code that does not conform to them is considered broken and mercilessly scrapped. ...Internet-Drafts are not specifications; software implementers and vendors are specifically barred from claiming compliance with them as if they were specifications. Internet-Drafts are focal points for discussion, usually in a working group... Once an Internet-Draft has been published with an RFC number, it is a specification to which implementers may claim conformance. It is expected that the authors of the RFC and the community at large will begin correcting the specification with field experience.
[End Tag        ] </q
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >

[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] "HTML+ Internet-Draft&nbsp;— Abstract"
[End Tag        ] </a
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] .
[Start Tag      ] <q
[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] Browser writers are experimenting with extensions to HTML and it is now appropriate to draw these ideas together into a revised document format. The new format is designed to allow a gradual roll over from HTML, adding features like tables, captioned figures and fill-out forms for querying remote databases or mailing questionnaires.
[End Tag        ] </q
[Tag End        ] >
[End Tag        ] </span
[Tag End        ] >

[Tag End        ] >
[Text           ] This document thus defines an HTML 2.0 (to distinguish it from the previous informal specifications). Future (generally upwardly compatible) versions of HTML with new features will be released with higher version numbers.

[Text           ] XHTML Documents which follow the guidelines set forth in Appendix C, "HTML Compatibility Guidelines" may be labeled with the Internet Media Type "text/html" [RFC2854], as they are compatible with most HTML browsers. Those documents, and any other document conforming to this specification, may also be labeled with the Internet Media Type "application/xhtml+xml" as defined in [RFC3236].
